    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "You can perform a simple visual test by clipping off a few yellowing leaves and examining the veins; if the veins stay green while the tissue turns yellow, it often points to nitrogen deficiency. To confirm this without guessing, you can mix a teaspoon of granular nitrogen fertilizer into the soil near the base of a leaf and water it in, then observe if the new growth starts to green up within a few days. If the issue is actually pests like spider mites or diseases like early blight, you'll likely find tiny webbing or dark spots on the leaves that a standard soil test won't catch. Always start with organic options like composted manure before applying heavy chemicals to avoid altering the soil's natural balance.",
