    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "It's not exactly that something is actively \"stealing\" the nutrients, but rather that nitrogen is a mobile nutrient that moves from older leaves (the yellow ones you see) to the new growth to keep the plant alive. Yes, soil type plays a huge role; heavy clay can hold onto nitrogen too tightly for the plant to access, while sandy soil might let it leach away into the groundwater if you overwater. This is why adding organic matter like compost helps lock the nitrogen in place so your plant can actually use it.",
